      <p>and <italic>P</italic><sub><italic>ab </italic></sub>is the probability of substitution between bases <italic>a </italic>and <italic>b </italic>(i.e., <italic>a</italic>, <italic>b </italic>in {<italic>A</italic>, <italic>C</italic>, <italic>G</italic>, <italic>T</italic>}), computed under a standard model of molecular evolution, such that <italic>P </italic>= <italic>e</italic><sup><italic>Rt </italic></sup>where <italic>R </italic>are the instantaneous rates of substitution and <italic>t </italic>is time (see Methods). The dotted trace in Figure <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F1">1b</xref> shows the distribution of ΔS for binding sites evolving in the absence of constraint.</p>
      <p>In a practical setting, we expect to have observed some relatively modest number (<italic>N</italic>) of substitutions in characterized binding sites. Therefore, in order to test the significance of a set of observed ΔS values, I propose the statistic:</p>
